gious Pseudoscience. Can Hume Help? -- tPART V. True Believers and Their Tactics -- t15. Argumentation and Pseudoscience The Case for an Ethics of Argumentation -- t16. Why Alternative Medicine Can Be Scientifically Evaluated Countering the Evasions of Pseudoscience. Countering the Evasions of Pseudoscience -- t17. Pseudoscience. The Case of Freud’s Sexual Etiology of the Neuroses -- t18. The Holocaust Denier’s Playbook and the Tobacco Smokescreen. Common Threads in the Thinking and Tactics of Denialists and Pseudoscientists -- tPART VI. The Cognitive Roots of Pseudoscience -- t19. Evolved to Be Irrational?. Evolutionary and Cognitive Foundations of Pseudosciences -- t20. Werewolves in Scientists’ Clothing. Understanding Pseudoscientific Cognition -- t21. The Salem Region. Two Mindsets about Science -- t22. Pseudoscience and Idiosyncratic Theories of Rational Belief -- t23. Agentive Thinking and Illusions of Understanding -- tContributor -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat sets the practice of rigorously tested, sound science apart from pseudoscience? In this volume, the contributors seek to answer this question, known to philosophers of science as “the demarcation problem.” This issue has a long history in philosophy, stretching as far back as the early twentieth century and the work of Karl Popper. But by the late 1980s, scholars in the field began to treat the demarcation problem as impossible to solve and futile to ponder. However, the essays that Massimo Pigliucci and Maarten Boudry have assembled in this volume make a rousing case for the unequivocal importance of reflecting on the separation between pseudoscience and sound science. Moreover, the demarcation problem is not a purely theoretical dilemma of mere academic interest: it affects parents’ decisions to vaccinate children and governments’ willingness to adopt policies that prevent climate change. Pseudoscience often mimics science, using the superficial language and trappings of actual scientific research to seem more respectable. Even a well-informed public can be taken in by such questionable theories dressed up as science. Pseudoscientific beliefs compete with sound science on the health pages of newspapers for media coverage and in laboratories for research funding. Now more than ever the ability to separate genuine scientific findings from spurious ones is vital, and The Philosophy of Pseudoscience provides ground for philosophers, sociologists, historians, and laypeople to make decisions about what science is or isn’t.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPseudoscience. 0aScience. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aphilosophical, philosopher, demarcation, problem, controversy, controversial, science, scientific, research, hypothesis, scientist, essay collection, misleading, 20th century, contemporary, modern, academic, scholarly, history, historical, karl popper, 1980s, theoretical, theory, vaccine, vaccinations, government, policy, public health, change, progress.1 aBlancke, Stefaan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoudry, Maarten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoudry, Maarten, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrindell, Sheralee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuekens, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCioffi, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleland, Carol E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Smedt, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFales, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFor